docs.abstract: Satya Nadella’s memoir, “Hit Refresh,” enters the hardcover nonfiction list at No. 5.
docs.snippet: Satya Nadella’s memoir, “Hit Refresh,” enters the hardcover nonfiction list at No. 5.
docs.lead_paragraph: MICROSOFT WORDS: It’s been three years since Satya Nadella replaced Steve Ballmer as chief executive of Microsoft — just long enough, it seems, to write a book, “Hit Refresh,” all about how Nadella is a different kind of leader running a different kind of company. “It’s not that we had lost our soul,” Nadella writes (dubiously, in a book whose subtitle invokes the “Quest to Rediscover Microsoft’s Soul”), “but we needed renewal, a renaissance.” Elsewhere he sounds like a bummed-out consultant: “Employees were tired. They were frustrated. They were fed up with losing and falling behind. … They came to Microsoft with big dreams, but it felt like all they really did was deal with upper management, execute taxing processes and bicker in meetings.” In other words, they were shocked to find they worked in corporate America.

headline.main: Microsoft’s Chief Wants You to Know He’s a Different Kind of Leader
